In mathematics, the domain and range of a binary relation are two sets that are associated with the relation. The domain is the set of all elements that can be on the left-hand side of an ordered pair in the relation, and the range is the set of all elements that can be on the right-hand side of an ordered pair in the relation.

For example, the relation "is greater than" on the set of real numbers has domain all real numbers and range all real numbers greater than zero. This is because for any real number x, the ordered pair (x, y) is in the relation if and only if y is greater than x.

The domain and range of a binary relation can be determined by looking at the definition of the relation. In some cases, the domain and range may be obvious from the definition. In other cases, it may be necessary to do some work to determine the domain and range.

The domain and range of a binary relation are important because they can be used to describe the properties of the relation. For example, a relation is said to be a function if and only if every element in the domain is related to exactly one element in the range.

Here are some additional facts about domain and range:

* The domain and range of a binary relation are always subsets of the sets that the relation is defined on.
* The domain and range of a binary relation can be the same set.
* The domain and range of a binary relation can be disjoint sets.
* The domain and range of a binary relation can be empty sets.

