The domain and range of a binary relation are two sets that are associated with the relation. The domain is the set of all elements that can be on the left-hand side of an ordered pair in the relation, and the range is the set of all elements that can be on the right-hand side of an ordered pair in the relation.

To determine the domain and range of a binary relation, we can use the following steps:

1. Identify the set that the relation is defined on.
2. For each element in the set, check if it is possible to form an ordered pair with that element as the left-hand side. If it is possible, then the element is in the domain.
3. For each ordered pair in the relation, check if the right-hand side element is in the set. If it is, then the right-hand side element is in the range.

Once we have determined the domain and range of a binary relation, we can use them to describe the properties of the relation. For example, a relation is said to be a function if and only if every element in the domain is related to exactly one element in the range.

Here are some examples of binary relations and their domains and ranges:

* The relation "is greater than" on the set of real numbers has domain all real numbers and range all real numbers greater than zero.
* The relation "is equal to" on the set of integers has domain and range all integers.
* The relation "is a parent of" on the set of people has domain all people and range all people who have at least one child.

